WEBVTT

00:11.780 --> 00:16.780
Subtitles by explosiveskull

00:16.782 --> 00:18.518
[911 operator]
<i>911, what's your emergency?</i>

00:18.520 --> 00:22.819
[man] <i>Yeah, um, could you please
send someone to 452 Meredith Lane?</i>

00:22.821 --> 00:26.423
<i>We have, um, some,
some bodies here.</i>

00:26.425 --> 00:27.493
<i>Do you need medical?</i>

00:27.827 --> 00:29.560
<i>Um, no, no, ma'am.</i>

00:29.562 --> 00:31.164
<i>All right, so the parties
are deceased?</i>

00:31.696 --> 00:33.132
- <i>Yes.</i>
- <i>Are you safe?</i>

00:33.365 --> 00:34.564
<i>Yeah, we're the neighbors.</i>

00:34.566 --> 00:36.500
<i>We, we heard some shots
and came over and...</i>

00:36.502 --> 00:37.771
<i>Is there anyone
else in the house?</i>

00:38.972 --> 00:41.338
<i>Just a little girl.
She's upstairs with my wife.</i>

00:41.340 --> 00:43.209
<i>Okay, someone will
be there right away.</i>

00:43.642 --> 00:44.711
<i>Thank you.</i>

00:45.444 --> 00:48.248
[multiple voices
cheering and advising]

00:50.649 --> 00:52.118
- That's it.
- That's it.

00:52.685 --> 00:54.054
[coach] Nice, girls, nice.

00:55.287 --> 00:56.454
[Miranda Ruth] <i>I don't know,
I just feel like when</i>

00:56.456 --> 00:58.224
<i>these so-called skeptics
of any and all...</i>

00:59.557 --> 01:02.425
<i>religious faiths,
spirituality, metaphysics...</i>

01:02.427 --> 01:04.230
whatever you wanna
call it,

01:05.197 --> 01:08.464
are tempted to shut
the idea out completely...

01:08.466 --> 01:12.771
I think that it's important that the
question be asked, what is the difference

01:13.605 --> 01:18.444
between the material that they talk
about and study and meditate upon,

01:19.378 --> 01:22.379
and the spirit
which we talk about

01:22.381 --> 01:24.150
and study and meditate upon.

01:24.917 --> 01:28.588
Is there actually a difference?
Or is it really just...

01:29.287 --> 01:32.191
a different way
of thinking or of seeing?

01:33.292 --> 01:35.495
And I'm not so sure
that there is a difference.

01:37.296 --> 01:39.163
Anyway, these are just...
they are some of the ideas

01:39.165 --> 01:40.867
that I hope
come across in the novel.

01:43.302 --> 01:45.371
All right, I'm, I'm out of words.
[chuckles]

01:45.638 --> 01:47.404
[interviewer]
I'm sure that's not true.

01:47.406 --> 01:49.843
But that does
bring us to a close.

01:50.275 --> 01:51.643
So I wanna thank you all
for being here

01:53.012 --> 01:55.244
and a very special thanks to Miranda
Ruth for making time for us.

01:55.246 --> 01:56.448
You're welcome.

01:59.284 --> 02:02.588
[quiet chattering]

02:07.760 --> 02:11.296
[cellphone vibrating]

02:16.835 --> 02:19.205
I need to take this. Excuse me.

02:23.375 --> 02:25.741
[Jason Loughlin] <i>I just think
getting away would be good for her,</i>

02:25.743 --> 02:27.881
<i>good for both of us, actually.</i>

02:28.479 --> 02:30.316
<i>We've been going at each other
a lot lately.</i>

02:30.549 --> 02:33.552
<i>And she's interested in Chicago
for college, so yeah.</i>

02:33.752 --> 02:39.989
Well... I'm not sure how exciting I'd
be but of course I'd love to have her.

02:39.991 --> 02:43.762
- Um, how long?
- <i>I don't know. Couple of weeks?</i>

02:46.365 --> 02:49.903
That would be fine. Um...
When were you thinking?

02:50.868 --> 02:52.604
<i>As soon as possible.</i>

02:54.406 --> 02:57.911
Okay, yeah, um, yeah,
we can make that work, sure.

02:58.610 --> 03:00.947
[female] ...opportunity for
some literary contest...

03:02.681 --> 03:05.315
- Family.
- Everything okay?

03:05.317 --> 03:06.319
Yes.

03:07.453 --> 03:10.890
[jazz music playing
in background]

03:22.568 --> 03:25.237
[upbeat music playing]

03:32.610 --> 03:36.515
<i>♪ I aim to please But I don't
know how to get there ♪</i>

03:37.049 --> 03:39.583
<i>♪ So I guess
it's how I end up here ♪</i>

03:39.585 --> 03:42.222
<i>♪ Pumping poison
through my veins ♪</i>

03:43.521 --> 03:47.359
<i>♪ I aim to leave
Find a way out of my own hell ♪</i>

03:48.294 --> 03:53.266
<i>♪ I push and pull and then I tell
myself to remember the names ♪</i>

03:54.599 --> 04:00.436
<i>♪ Of the people
you met in December ♪</i>

04:00.438 --> 04:05.777
<i>♪ It's surreal, it's true
It's hard to remember ♪</i>

04:09.747 --> 04:11.917
[birds chirping]

04:14.485 --> 04:15.988
[Cyd Loughlin] Thank you. Yeah.

04:19.490 --> 04:21.493
[Miranda chuckles]

04:21.726 --> 04:23.996
[Miranda] Oh, my God!

04:26.464 --> 04:28.267
- You grew up. Hey.
- [Cyd chuckles]

04:28.600 --> 04:29.701
Hi.

04:31.970 --> 04:34.407
Oh, welcome, sweetheart.

04:35.841 --> 04:37.776
- Thanks.
- Um-hmm, come on then.

04:38.976 --> 04:40.947
- How was your flight?
- A little bumpy.

04:41.346 --> 04:44.283
- Yeah? Oh, can I get that?
- Oh, no, no, no, thanks, I got it.

04:45.016 --> 04:46.750
You were little
when you were last here.

04:46.752 --> 04:48.454
You probably don't
remember this place.

04:48.786 --> 04:50.989
I do... now.

04:52.790 --> 04:55.862
I live upstairs. So why don't you
come on in, we'll get you settled.

05:05.803 --> 05:08.807
- And here it is.
- Oh.

05:09.375 --> 05:11.043
Small but it's cozy.

05:11.944 --> 05:13.743
The light is brilliant
in the morning.

05:13.745 --> 05:18.050
And a chair in the corner makes
for a really nice reading nook.

05:18.483 --> 05:19.786
Oh, I don't really read.

05:21.987 --> 05:27.060
Well, there're some real gems on the
bookshelf if you decide to give it a go.

05:29.961 --> 05:31.396
Do you have WiFi?

05:31.596 --> 05:34.930
I do. Uh, RalphWaldo
is the name of it.

05:34.932 --> 05:37.836
- Okay.
- And the password is...

05:38.437 --> 05:41.441
all caps...
Hawthorne with an e...

05:42.007 --> 05:43.709
eighteen fifty.

05:45.177 --> 05:47.579
And that's the year that <i>The Scarlet
Letter</i> was... you don't care.

05:47.812 --> 05:49.514
Got it. Thank you.

05:51.115 --> 05:53.051
That's the year <i>The Scarlet
Letter</i> was published?

05:53.451 --> 05:54.584
Yeah, yeah.

05:54.586 --> 05:56.719
- Cool. [chuckles]
- Are you hungry?

05:56.721 --> 05:57.820
Uh, yeah. A little.

05:57.822 --> 05:59.990
Um... well, just get settled

05:59.992 --> 06:02.692
and whenever you're ready
come down and we eat.

06:02.694 --> 06:03.862
Thanks.

06:09.201 --> 06:11.037
This was your mom's room,
by the way.

06:29.788 --> 06:31.555
Hey, I'm just about ready.

06:31.557 --> 06:33.957
Um, you can go take a peek
out back if you like,

06:33.959 --> 06:35.595
I think that's where
we're gonna eat lunch.

06:38.029 --> 06:39.498
Do you eat potato salad?
Oh, shit!

06:39.898 --> 06:41.667
- What?
- Are you vegetarian?

06:43.968 --> 06:47.173
- I'm sorry. I have...
- No, no, no, no... [laughs]

06:47.605 --> 06:49.105
- You're not?
- No, I'm kidding. [laughs]

06:49.107 --> 06:50.510
You're so bad.

07:46.865 --> 07:49.468
Your dad told me that you were thinking
about coming up here for college?

07:49.668 --> 07:51.901
- That's exciting.
- Yeah, maybe.

07:51.903 --> 07:54.473
Um... it depends on where
I can get a scholarship.

07:56.108 --> 08:00.045
Well, your mom went to DePaul, of course,
and that's a good one... and, um...

08:00.612 --> 08:04.817
UFC, University of Chicago, that's
where I teach occasionally.

08:06.584 --> 08:08.920
Although, they're a little nuts
there so... [Cyd chuckles]

08:09.153 --> 08:10.152
...might want to
avoid that one.

08:10.154 --> 08:12.557
[laughs]
Okay. Will do.

08:16.194 --> 08:21.501
What about you? Um, how's...
books, how's books and stuff?

08:23.701 --> 08:25.170
Books and stuff are good.
[chuckles]

08:25.937 --> 08:27.637
I've been doing
I feel a lot of press

08:27.639 --> 08:30.339
for this new thing,
uh, this novel...

08:30.341 --> 08:33.078
- Hmm, what's it called?
- <i>In the Dawn.</i>

08:34.046 --> 08:36.649
- What's it about?
- Oh, really?

08:38.115 --> 08:39.682
Well, it's about... [sighs]

08:39.683 --> 08:41.818
It's about this woman
named Jacqueline,

08:41.820 --> 08:43.756
and on her 50th birthday, she...

08:44.822 --> 08:47.225
- You sure you want to hear this?
- Sure.

08:48.059 --> 08:51.296
Um, what else are we gonna talk about?
[both chuckle]

08:51.763 --> 08:54.066
Good point. Um...

08:54.899 --> 08:55.967
So on her 50th birthday,

08:57.034 --> 08:58.169
she starts to become
extra sensitive to the sun,

08:59.236 --> 09:02.872
um, it starts to affect her...
her relationships,

09:02.874 --> 09:05.644
her friendships, her work...

09:06.144 --> 09:08.277
Uh... well,
I'm not sure how much

09:08.279 --> 09:10.379
you really want
me to tell you...

09:10.381 --> 09:12.250
- but...
- You can tell me all of it.

09:13.884 --> 09:15.187
That's no fun.

09:15.821 --> 09:17.286
Well... isn't that, like,

09:17.288 --> 09:18.890
what you're supposed to do
with stories?

09:19.658 --> 09:21.693
Well... yeah,
but I mean when you...

09:23.394 --> 09:26.363
worked for two years on the
heart of it... [chuckles]

09:26.365 --> 09:28.301
Okay, but I'm not gonna read it.

09:30.735 --> 09:31.870
Fair enough.

09:33.739 --> 09:37.643
Um... well, come to find out
she's been doing a lot of...

09:38.110 --> 09:41.945
research on, uh, on this
condition called photo phobia...

09:41.947 --> 09:42.947
Is that real?

09:44.048 --> 09:45.848
It is, but in my version
it's a little heightened.

09:45.850 --> 09:47.186
Um, anyway, so she...

09:49.086 --> 09:51.921
she's doing this research
and then she realizes

09:51.923 --> 09:55.995
that it dates back centuries
in her own family and, uh...

09:56.727 --> 09:59.963
it's original name,
Aether Evaisthis'a,

09:59.965 --> 10:02.201
actually comes from a Greek god.

10:03.100 --> 10:05.037
- So, she...
- Oh, you write fantasy?

10:05.736 --> 10:09.074
No, no, I don't write fantasy.
A lot of my work has some...

10:09.908 --> 10:11.940
some metaphysical themes
and some spiritual themes

10:11.942 --> 10:13.678
but it's realism.

10:14.245 --> 10:16.215
- Um... it's true...
- Sounds like fantasy. [chuckles]

10:16.782 --> 10:18.684
No, no, it's not. It's...

10:19.350 --> 10:21.751
Um, so... she, uh,

10:21.753 --> 10:24.857
decides to go Greece
to get to the bottom of this...

10:25.289 --> 10:27.325
and then when she gets there,
she gets into this...

10:36.735 --> 10:38.169
[sighs deeply]

10:47.479 --> 10:49.849
[Jason Loughlin] Be good to see
where your mom came from, huh?

11:04.129 --> 11:06.432
[light flute music playing]

11:46.270 --> 11:48.740
[rhythmic tapping on door]

11:51.475 --> 11:54.279
- Hey.
- [Anthony James] Hey, doll!

11:54.879 --> 11:57.347
We could have rescheduled. I didn't
mean to mess up time with your niece.

11:57.349 --> 11:59.382
Oh, no, no.
She's running some...

11:59.384 --> 12:01.353
We may never see her again.

12:02.019 --> 12:03.722
I haven't seen her
since she was...

12:04.956 --> 12:07.357
She must have been eight,
that's right after the funeral.

12:07.359 --> 12:09.124
I heard she was there
when it happened.

12:09.126 --> 12:13.028
Yes, fast asleep but...
yeah, she was in the house.

12:13.030 --> 12:14.099
Jesus!

12:16.534 --> 12:18.236
- She plays soccer.
- [Anthony chuckles]

12:18.570 --> 12:20.002
Whatever will you talk about?

12:20.004 --> 12:23.806
Ha, I...
That's the thing, I'm scared.

12:23.808 --> 12:26.044
And she seems funny,
she's smart but...

12:27.379 --> 12:29.447
I don't know,
hopefully she likes me.

12:30.148 --> 12:31.283
Rest assured.

12:33.552 --> 12:36.585
So, okay. Where did we...
Where did we leave off?

12:36.587 --> 12:39.388
Uh, part two,
chapter one but we can

12:39.390 --> 12:42.026
backtrack if you've got
any structural...

12:42.394 --> 12:44.493
How is our timing?
When are you showing this...

12:44.495 --> 12:46.064
I told them late summer.

12:46.498 --> 12:47.564
- Oh!
- Yeah.

12:47.566 --> 12:49.531
Well, then, it'll be fine
'cause I really think

12:49.533 --> 12:52.035
the second half, it's just more
about what can come out...

12:52.037 --> 12:55.341
- Rather than any drastic...
- Right, any drastic changes.

12:55.974 --> 12:59.142
Uh... but I will say
if we can back it up...

12:59.144 --> 13:00.475
I thought we might
want to zero in...

13:00.477 --> 13:02.947
If we can back it up
to the end of part one...

13:03.881 --> 13:06.384
um...
I just think it's sort of...

13:07.184 --> 13:10.052
No, it's these two opposing
problems that are dividing the book

13:10.054 --> 13:11.856
a third of the way in.
Um...

13:12.356 --> 13:14.894
the inner part one's characterization,
they're beautiful...

13:15.226 --> 13:18.261
They really are,
but I mentioned that last week

13:18.263 --> 13:19.863
I just think that
the information is just being

13:19.865 --> 13:21.466
kind of clunkily laid out.

13:21.899 --> 13:24.400
Right, which I personally
disagree with.

13:24.402 --> 13:26.469
Right, but that's why
you have come to your

13:26.471 --> 13:28.604
brilliant writer friend Miranda.

13:28.606 --> 13:30.873
- For her ideas.
- I have indeed.

13:30.875 --> 13:33.111
- Just so we're clear.
- And we are.

13:33.879 --> 13:35.445
Um...

13:35.447 --> 13:38.915
So you're starting with this
beautiful study momentum

13:38.917 --> 13:42.153
<i>at the top of part two with DeAndre
and the trail of the journalist.</i>

13:43.087 --> 13:46.256
<i>This is the smoothest most
energized passage in this book.</i>

13:46.258 --> 13:49.358
<i>And then you do
earn in chapter 12,</i>

13:49.360 --> 13:52.362
<i>this breathing space,
this nice patient</i>

13:52.364 --> 13:56.067
<i>lull that relaxes
and speaks to us.</i>

13:57.001 --> 13:59.535
<i>But once the journalist,
I don't know what his name is...</i>

13:59.537 --> 14:02.341
- <i>Earnest.</i>
- <i>Once he throws himself off the bridge,</i>

14:02.673 --> 14:04.206
<i>leaving DeAndre alone,
I think</i>

14:04.208 --> 14:06.978
<i>that's when the book is telling
you, you need to move.</i>

14:07.278 --> 14:08.447
<i>Just move, move, move.</i>

14:09.280 --> 14:12.584
So the philosophical tangents
in parts two and part three,

14:13.217 --> 14:16.685
they probably just need to go.
That's my biggest...

14:16.687 --> 14:19.321
I know, I ca... I can't believe
that I'm saying that.

14:19.323 --> 14:21.456
Who are you and
what have you done with Miranda?

14:21.458 --> 14:22.460
Right?

14:43.248 --> 14:44.550
[bell jingles]

14:45.115 --> 14:46.251
- [Cyd] Hi!
- [male] Hi.

14:47.352 --> 14:49.954
- Uh, I think I'm lost.
- Where're you trying to be?

14:50.322 --> 14:52.055
- Raven something...
- Ravenswood?

14:52.057 --> 14:54.357
Yes, but there's something else.

14:54.359 --> 14:55.427
[Katie Sauter] Gardens.

14:56.226 --> 14:57.663
Uh, yeah, yeah, that's it.

14:58.363 --> 15:01.064
East of the bridge. You're
actually in the right road.

15:01.066 --> 15:03.398
Just head straight west
a few blocks.

15:03.400 --> 15:05.535
It should start
to look familiar.

15:05.537 --> 15:07.506
Okay, thanks. Thanks.

15:17.381 --> 15:19.114
I didn't say the ending

15:19.116 --> 15:21.316
wasn't justified. I just said
it doesn't currently work.

15:21.318 --> 15:22.654
Because of the tangents?

15:24.188 --> 15:26.122
Possibly but it's also possible that
it doesn't work despite the tangents.

15:26.124 --> 15:27.558
Good lord. [Anthony laughs]

15:28.559 --> 15:30.660
I... Hey!

15:30.662 --> 15:32.362
Hey, sorry.
I can go back outside.

15:32.364 --> 15:35.968
No, no, no, no, no.
We were just having a discourse.

15:36.167 --> 15:38.237
Uh, Cyd,
this is my friend Anthony.

15:38.702 --> 15:40.238
- Hi.
- Hiya, Cyd.

15:40.739 --> 15:43.006
Anthony is an old
writer friend of mine.

15:43.008 --> 15:44.677
"Old writer friend,"
how flattering.

15:45.110 --> 15:49.315
Old Pulitzer Prize nominated
writer friend of mine, how's that?

15:49.748 --> 15:52.482
Anthony is
a well-respected journalist,

15:52.484 --> 15:55.350
writer of non-fiction
and now he's writing a novel,

15:55.352 --> 15:57.719
That's what we were discussing.

15:57.721 --> 16:00.223
Now he has to go talk about
the election on television.

16:00.225 --> 16:02.461
- Cool!
- I'd rather be doing anything else.

16:03.794 --> 16:06.396
Um, I'm gonna go take a shower.
I smell bad.

16:06.398 --> 16:08.567
Okay, there are towels right
outside the door on the shelf.

16:09.533 --> 16:11.334
- Nice to meet you, Cyd.
- Yeah, nice to meet you too.

16:11.336 --> 16:12.738
- See you Friday?
- Uh?

16:13.804 --> 16:16.039
Oh! The soiree?

16:16.041 --> 16:20.045
I haven't even told you about that yet.
All in good time. Yeah.

16:24.182 --> 16:26.217
I'm out. Thanks for this.

16:27.317 --> 16:29.020
It's really good, Anthony.

16:30.654 --> 16:33.192
Anyway, my thoughts are my thoughts.
It's your book.

16:36.461 --> 16:38.629
I know. [laughs]

16:39.831 --> 16:42.565
- How's Brandon?
- Oh, he's fine. He's fine.

16:42.567 --> 16:44.400
He's with his mom this week.

16:44.402 --> 16:47.536
Take him to his first Cub's
game for his 15th birthday

16:47.538 --> 16:49.772
- but he doesn't know it yet.
- Aw! He'll love that.

16:49.774 --> 16:51.076
I think so.

16:55.312 --> 16:57.149
- See you Friday.
- Bye.

17:19.304 --> 17:20.471
Wow.

17:26.611 --> 17:28.347
So what's the deal
with your friend?

17:29.480 --> 17:30.582
The deal?

17:31.382 --> 17:33.349
Uh, well...

17:33.351 --> 17:37.620
Anthony and I went to the
University of Chicago years ago

17:37.622 --> 17:41.692
when we were grad students.
Then we became fast friends.

17:42.794 --> 17:44.630
So, no romance?

17:45.230 --> 17:48.166
What? Oh, my God! No, no.

17:48.633 --> 17:50.565
Why, why do you ask?

17:50.567 --> 17:52.637
Just curious. He seemed nice.

17:53.805 --> 17:56.642
He is and a brilliant mind.

17:57.608 --> 17:58.810
He's handsome.

18:01.378 --> 18:04.348
He is. You should see his son.

18:05.282 --> 18:07.350
This beautiful boy.
He's gonna...

18:07.352 --> 18:08.918
swoop up all the ladies...

18:08.920 --> 18:12.157
[chuckles]
one day or the man or both.

18:14.692 --> 18:17.426
Anyway, he's married,
um, technically.

18:17.428 --> 18:20.199
What about you?
Do you have a boyfriend?

18:20.798 --> 18:23.501
- Yeah, kinda.
- Kinda?

18:25.569 --> 18:27.472
Mmm, wonderful.

18:27.771 --> 18:29.505
Anything else
I can get you ladies?

18:29.507 --> 18:31.740
No! I think this is fine.

18:31.742 --> 18:34.343
- Thank you, Sarah.
- My pleasure, Ms. Ruth. Enjoy.

18:34.345 --> 18:35.380
Thanks.

18:36.780 --> 18:39.248
She's wonderful. She's so sweet.

18:39.250 --> 18:41.854
- [exhales] So much food.
- I know.

18:42.886 --> 18:45.720
Are you sure you don't want
something other than just water?

18:45.722 --> 18:48.594
- Oh, yeah. I'm fine, thanks.
- Good for you.

18:50.795 --> 18:52.698
So did you come here
a lot growing up?

18:53.498 --> 18:55.734
Oh, yeah.
We came at least once a week.

18:56.800 --> 18:58.769
Your mom and I would get
pretty sick of it.

18:59.570 --> 19:03.307
- But, uh... now I love it.
- Cool.

19:07.644 --> 19:10.781
- So, uh... so the boy?
- What? Oh.

19:11.682 --> 19:15.520
