<i>♪ The truth of the matter ♪</i>

49:11.414 --> 49:16.653
<i>♪ Is from the shadows
It was staring me in the face ♪</i>

49:19.389 --> 49:23.124
<i>♪ Would have lost myself
In the desert ♪</i>

49:23.126 --> 49:28.065
<i>♪ Of the hearts
that life tarnishing, Debased ♪</i>

49:37.606 --> 49:40.277
We were rivals. She was a prosecutor.
I was a DA.

49:40.543 --> 49:41.611
That's so cool.

49:42.577 --> 49:43.577
Oh, we should also add
that I was married.

49:43.579 --> 49:45.345
Yes, so, in any case

49:45.347 --> 49:47.313
we knew we had to wait
until one of us retired

49:47.315 --> 49:49.349
so we could successfully
make a go at it.

49:49.351 --> 49:51.487
- [guest] You worked on the same case?
- Cases.

49:52.255 --> 49:53.423
That's incredible.

49:53.688 --> 49:54.921
So you were both married to men?

49:54.923 --> 49:58.659
Um, yes. I was a widow when we
met, I was a widow early on.

49:58.661 --> 50:02.699
Bettie was married, got divorced later.
That's where he came from.

50:03.800 --> 50:07.037
So you liked it and you didn't?

50:09.304 --> 50:10.539
What, being married to men?

50:12.175 --> 50:13.543
Are you asking if we like dick?

50:13.809 --> 50:15.411
[all choking with laughter]

50:15.677 --> 50:17.146
Um...

50:25.855 --> 50:28.255
I did. She didn't.

50:28.257 --> 50:29.559
I do.

50:33.663 --> 50:35.231
Dick is not terrible, is it?

50:35.565 --> 50:38.467
It's not terrible, it is like
the opposite of terrible.

50:40.836 --> 50:42.304
So what are you into, hon?

50:44.706 --> 50:47.641
Oh, um... I...

50:47.643 --> 50:51.481
like... everything.

50:55.585 --> 50:59.755
[Evergreen James] ...and he goes outside
to go on his little date to the dance

51:00.222 --> 51:03.490
and in two seconds,
he comes back in and he's like,

51:03.492 --> 51:07.427
"Mama, her parents left.
We need a ride."

51:07.429 --> 51:09.463
[Anthony] Right. I don't think
that's exactly what happened

51:09.465 --> 51:10.898
but whatever.

51:10.900 --> 51:14.434
Oh, shut up.
I drove you on all your dates.

51:14.436 --> 51:16.806
Yes, you did and I love you, Mama.
Thank you.

51:17.773 --> 51:20.644
I can drive you two,
if you wanna go somewhere.

51:24.547 --> 51:25.648
Wow.

51:30.686 --> 51:32.655
Where's J?
Thought he was coming home.

51:33.188 --> 51:35.257
- He got himself a date.
- Really?

51:35.625 --> 51:36.760
Uh-hmm.

51:38.460 --> 51:40.629
- Some girl at work.
- Weird.

51:41.597 --> 51:42.799
We were supposed to hang out.

51:43.498 --> 51:44.767
How are you?

51:47.536 --> 51:50.172
- Fine. How are you?
- I'm good.

51:50.706 --> 51:55.211
I'm sorry for making fun of you in
front of your friend the other day,

51:55.844 --> 51:58.781
when I like picked you up
and spun you around.

51:59.248 --> 52:01.818
- So what are you up to tonight?
- Don't know.

52:02.617 --> 52:04.453
Let me know if
you wanna hang out.

52:05.188 --> 52:07.423
Uh... okay.

52:09.391 --> 52:13.163
[people speaking on television]

52:14.362 --> 52:15.662
[female guest] <i>This is a story</i>

52:15.664 --> 52:18.768
about a woman who burnt
her own house down.

52:19.202 --> 52:22.869
- Not true. Okay.
- No, sir. [laughs] This is very true.

52:22.871 --> 52:26.408
- Okay, okay.
- This is very, very true. 1968.

52:26.708 --> 52:29.411
- Cincinnati, Ohio...
- Mmm, no, no, no cellphones.

52:29.711 --> 52:32.349
- Oh, sorry.
- [crowd murmurs]

52:32.547 --> 52:35.384
Sweet... sweet Cincinnati.

52:36.351 --> 52:40.723
Dolores... mother of four, worked
for the Ohio insurance company.

52:41.623 --> 52:44.226
Husband left her
for another woman.

52:45.293 --> 52:48.498
Left her alone in that house
with four children.

52:48.998 --> 52:50.666
Three boys, one girl.

52:51.701 --> 52:53.503
One day,
someone knocks on her door.

52:53.936 --> 52:57.807
She opens it to find a very nice
seeming young man standing there.

52:58.407 --> 53:02.245
He is new to town. Works for the paper.
Looking to rent a place.

53:03.246 --> 53:05.012
Money is tight for them, see?

53:05.014 --> 53:07.313
So she moves into
her daughter's bedroom,

53:07.315 --> 53:09.516
gives the nice young man
the nice room

53:09.518 --> 53:11.454
just till he gets off
the ground here.

53:12.021 --> 53:14.758
Good Christian man.
Not a concern in the world.

53:16.559 --> 53:20.597
Couple of days later, she catches word
a woman in Columbus was murdered.

53:20.862 --> 53:23.567
- [all] Ooh.
- By a devil worshiper.

53:23.766 --> 53:25.733
[all] Woo!

53:25.735 --> 53:28.001
- And he got away.
- [elderly female] Woo! Oh, dear.

53:28.003 --> 53:30.470
Oh, don't worry.
I don't think it's true.

53:30.472 --> 53:32.305
What... did you say?

53:32.307 --> 53:33.574
[all laughing]

53:33.576 --> 53:37.447
I said, "Yeah, you know, I think
I read about that somewhere."

53:39.447 --> 53:40.516
Damn right.

53:40.983 --> 53:42.318
Is she okay?

53:43.519 --> 53:44.686
Yeah, she's, uh, just pregnant
so she's really sensitive.

53:44.688 --> 53:49.690
- Whoa! Hey! Congratulations!
- [female] Congratulations!

53:49.692 --> 53:51.958
No! No...

53:51.960 --> 53:54.697
- I didn't. It just came out.
- Bravo.

53:55.530 --> 53:57.333
Congratulations.

53:57.800 --> 54:00.237
- Should we tell them what it's gonna be?
- No! Zip it!

54:04.907 --> 54:06.639
"There's a certain
slant of light,

54:06.641 --> 54:09.378
winter afternoons,
that oppresses,

54:09.778 --> 54:11.681
like the heft
of cathedral tunes...

54:12.882 --> 54:14.483
Heavenly hurt, it gives us.

54:14.849 --> 54:18.788
We can find no scar,
but internal difference,

54:19.588 --> 54:21.324
where the meanings are.

54:22.358 --> 54:24.027
None may teach it, any.

54:24.860 --> 54:26.863
'Tis the seal despair,

54:27.730 --> 54:30.666
an imperial affliction
sent us of the Air...

54:31.567 --> 54:35.639
When it comes, the landscape listens...
Shadows hold their breath

54:36.539 --> 54:41.745
When it goes, ‘tis like the
distance on the look of death.

54:44.112 --> 54:46.380
- Emily Dickinson.
- Yeah.

54:46.382 --> 54:50.019
I have... a memory, an impression
when I read this poem.

54:50.853 --> 54:53.519
Did you ever get the feeling
when you were a child

54:53.521 --> 54:57.793
the end of August when the first
little chill comes in the evening,

54:58.027 --> 55:02.298
- and you're thinking, "School starts"?
- [all laugh]

55:02.731 --> 55:04.430
End of summer blues.

55:04.432 --> 55:07.367
"Behind what we think of
as the Russian menace

55:07.369 --> 55:10.440
lies what we do not wish to face
when they regard a negro.

55:11.072 --> 55:14.943
Reality, the fact that life
is tragic.

55:15.844 --> 55:18.711
Life is tragic simply because
the earth turns

55:18.713 --> 55:21.016
and the sun inexorably
rises and sets,

55:21.983 --> 55:23.853
and one day, for each of us,

55:24.519 --> 55:27.791
the sun will go down
for the last, last time.

55:29.023 --> 55:32.394
Perhaps the whole root of our
trouble, the human trouble,

55:32.628 --> 55:36.662
is that we will sacrifice
all the beauty of our lives,

55:36.664 --> 55:38.802
will imprison ourselves
in totems,

55:39.568 --> 55:41.071
taboos, crosses,

55:41.570 --> 55:44.740
blood sacrifices, steeples,
mosques, races,

55:44.940 --> 55:47.110
armies, flags, nations

55:47.610 --> 55:50.380
in order to deny
the fact of death.

55:50.880 --> 55:52.749
The only fact we have.

55:53.548 --> 55:57.885
It seems to me that one ought to
rejoice in the fact of death,

55:57.887 --> 56:01.088
ought to decide indeed
to earn one's death

56:01.090 --> 56:04.525
by confronting with passion
the conundrum of life..."

56:04.527 --> 56:07.764
"We sat looking off across the
country watching the sun go down.

56:08.597 --> 56:11.134
The curly grass about us
was on fire now,

56:12.168 --> 56:14.838
the bark of the oaks
turned red as copper,

56:15.103 --> 56:17.539
there was a shimmer of gold
on the brown river,

56:18.440 --> 56:21.474
out in the stream, the
sandbars glittered like glass

56:21.476 --> 56:23.913
and the light trembled
in the willow thickets

56:24.679 --> 56:27.817
as if little flames
were leaping among them.

56:29.083 --> 56:30.919
The breeze sank
into stillness..."

56:32.588 --> 56:34.987
"His soul swims slowly as he heard the
snow falling faintly through the universe,

56:34.989 --> 56:38.894
and faintly falling like the
descent of their last end

56:39.527 --> 56:41.997
upon all the living
and the dead."

56:43.498 --> 56:45.167
James Joyce, <i>The Dead.</i>

56:45.867 --> 56:47.871
[female guest] Hmm. Thank you.

56:52.106 --> 56:54.610
- [Tab] Hey
- What the fuck, man?

56:54.943 --> 56:57.146
I was wondering if you wanted to
sit on the bed with me.

56:57.713 --> 57:00.046
